public class Car {
    private String model;
    private String color;

    public Car(String model, String color) {
        this.model = model;
        this.color = color;
    }
}
In this example, the Car class has a constructor that takes two parameters: model and color. When a new Car object is created, the constructor is automatically called to initialize the model and color instance variables.

Method:

A method in Java is a block of code that performs a specific task or action when called.
Methods have a name, a return type (or void if they don't return a value), and can accept zero or more parameters.
Methods are explicitly called by name, either on objects (instance methods) or on the class itself (static methods).
Methods can have any number of statements, perform calculations, manipulate data, or execute specific operations.
Methods can be overloaded, which means you can have multiple methods with the same name but different parameter lists.
Methods are typically used to encapsulate functionality, organize code into reusable units, and provide a way to interact with objects.
Here's an example of a method:

